'''Alex North''' ([[December 4]], [[1910]] - [[September 8]], [[1991]]) was an [[United States|American]]  [[composer]] responsible for the first [[jazz]] based [[film score]] (''[[A Streetcar Named Desire (film)|A Streetcar Named Desire]]'') and the first truly [[modernism|modernist]] film score (''[[Viva Zapata!]]'').

Born "Isadore Soifer" in [[Chester, Pennsylvania]], Alex North was an original composer probably even by the classical music standards of the day.
However, he managed to integrate his [[modernism]] into typical film music leitmotif structure, rich with themes. One of these became the famous song, "[[Unchained Melody]]". Nominated for 15 [[Academy_Awards|Oscars]] but unsuccessful each time, Alex North and [[Ennio Morricone]] are the only [[film composer|film composers]] to receive the [[Academy Honorary Award|Lifetime Achievement Academy Award]].

His most popular film scores of those many not already mentioned are ''[[The Rainmaker (1956 film)|The Rainmaker]]'' ([[1956 in film|1956]]), ''[[Spartacus (film)|Spartacus]]'' ([[1960 in film|1960]]), ''[[The Misfits (film)|The Misfits]]'' ([[1961 in film|1961]]), ''[[Cleopatra (1963 film)|Cleopatra]]'' ([[1963 in film|1963]]), ''[[Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf? (film)|Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?]]'' ([[1966 in film|1966]]), ''[[The Devil's Brigade (film)|The Devil's Brigade]]'' ([[1968 in film|1968]]),  and the [[2001: A Space Odyssey (score)|rejected score]] for [[Stanley Kubrick]]'s ''[[2001: A Space Odyssey (film)|2001: A Space Odyssey]]'' ([[1968 in film|1968]]). His classical works include a ''[[Rhapsody]] for [[Piano]], [[Trumpet]] [[obbligato]] and [[Orchestra]]''.

==Work on Broadway==

*''[[Mother]]'' [[(1935)]] - [[play]] with music - co-[[composer]]
*''[[Life and Death of an American]]'' ([[1939]]) - [[play]] - co-[[composer]]
*''[[Tis of Thee]]'' ([[1940]]) - [[revue]] - co-[[composer]]
*''[[Of V We Sing]]'' ([[1942]]) - [[revue]] - featured [[composer]]
*''[[Death of a Salesman]]'' ([[1949]]) - music for the [[play]] - [[composer]]
*''[[The Innocents]]'' ([[1950]]) - [[play]] - [[incidental music]] [[composer]]
*''[[A Streetcar Named Desire (ballet)|A Streetcar Named Desire]]'' ([[1952]]) - [[ballet]] based on the [[A Streetcar Named Desire (play)|play]] - [[composer]]
*''[[Street Corner Symphony]]'' ([[1997]]) - [[revue]] - featured [[songwriter]] for "Unchained Melody"

